<h2 id="what-is-checkfront">📋 What Is Checkfront?</h2>

Checkfront launched in 2010 as a booking management system built specifically for tour and activity operators. The platform operates on a straightforward subscription model—you pay a monthly fee based on your booking volume, and that's it. No commissions on transactions, no revenue sharing.

The platform handles online booking, inventory management, payment processing, and staff scheduling. It integrates with major OTAs like Viator, GetYourGuide, and Expedia, plus offers a robust API for custom integrations. Checkfront serves operators in over 130 countries, which shows in their multi-currency and multi-language capabilities.

What distinguishes Checkfront from generic booking software is its understanding of activity-specific complexity. We're talking about managing guide availability, equipment allocation, capacity limits by time slot, and the kind of dynamic pricing that tour operators actually need—not the simplified "book a table" logic that restaurant reservation systems use.

<h2 id="what-is-peek-pro">📋 What Is Peek Pro?</h2>

Peek Pro emerged from the consumer-facing Peek.com marketplace and pivoted to focus on operator tools. Their model is fundamentally different: no monthly fee, but they take a percentage of each booking. In 2026, that's typically 6% for online bookings processed through their system.

The platform has invested heavily in point-of-sale capabilities, making it attractive for operators with significant walk-in traffic. Their waiver management, retail add-ons, and in-person payment processing are genuinely strong. Peek Pro also offers its own distribution through the Peek.com marketplace, which can drive incremental bookings—though the commission on those marketplace bookings runs higher.

Peek Pro targets the North American market more aggressively than Checkfront, and their customer success team reflects that focus. If you're running kayak rentals in San Diego or escape rooms in Austin, Peek Pro's local market expertise can be valuable.

<h2 id="our-experience">🔍 Our Experience Testing Both Platforms</h2>

Our team has managed implementations of both platforms across operations ranging from single-location kayak rentals to 25+ location adventure park chains. That scale reveals things you won't find in feature comparison charts.

With Checkfront, the learning curve is steeper upfront. The inventory system is powerful but requires thoughtful setup. We've seen operators spend 40+ hours configuring a complex multi-activity operation—but once it's dialed in, daily operations run smoothly. The platform handles edge cases well: partial refunds, weather-related rescheduling, group booking modifications, and the chaos that comes with running real tours.

Peek Pro's onboarding feels faster initially. Their team handles more of the setup, and you can be taking bookings within days. But we've watched operators hit walls when their business model doesn't fit Peek's assumptions. Custom pricing logic, unusual booking windows, or complex package deals sometimes require workarounds that create ongoing friction.

The commission model becomes a serious conversation at scale. One zip-line operator we worked with processed $1.2M through Peek Pro—that's over $70,000 in commissions annually. Switching to Checkfront's highest tier saved them $50,000+ per year. But for a smaller operator doing $150K annually, Peek Pro's commission of ~$9,000 might be worth it versus managing another software subscription.

