<h2 id="key-features">⚙️ Key Features Comparison</h2>

<h3>Booking Management</h3>

Checkfront's booking engine handles complex inventory scenarios that trip up simpler systems. Think: a guided tour that requires one guide per six guests, uses equipment that's shared across multiple tour types, and has different capacity limits for morning versus afternoon departures. The system tracks all dependencies and prevents overbooking automatically.

Peek Pro's booking management is solid for straightforward operations but can struggle with shared resource conflicts. We've seen issues when the same guide is assigned to overlapping activities—the system doesn't always catch conflicts that Checkfront's dependency tracking would flag.

Both platforms offer real-time availability APIs, but Checkfront's is more granular. If you're building custom booking experiences or need tight integration with your website, Checkfront provides more control.

<h3>Point of Sale & Walk-ins</h3>

This is where Peek Pro shines. Their POS system was built for high-volume walk-in environments. The interface is fast, works well on tablets and phones, and handles the reality of selling to customers standing in front of you. Retail upsells, add-ons, and quick checkout flows are genuinely good.

Checkfront has POS capabilities, but they feel like an afterthought compared to the online booking experience. If walk-ins represent more than 30% of your revenue, this matters. The checkout flow has more friction, and your staff will notice the difference during busy periods.

<h3>Channel Management & OTA Integration</h3>

Both platforms connect to major OTAs, but the implementation quality varies. Checkfront's OTA connections are more reliable in our experience—fewer sync issues, better handling of cancellations, and more consistent pricing updates. Their integration with Viator's new API handles real-time inventory particularly well.

Peek Pro's OTA integrations work, but we've seen more instances of availability discrepancies and the resulting overbooking headaches. Their Peek.com marketplace integration is seamless (obviously), which matters if that channel drives meaningful volume for you.

For a deeper look at distribution strategy, check our guide on [multi-location booking management](/articles/multi-location-booking-management).

<h3>Reporting & Analytics</h3>

Checkfront's reporting is comprehensive but requires effort to extract insights. You'll likely export to spreadsheets for serious analysis. The data is all there—booking sources, revenue by activity, staff utilization—but the built-in dashboards are functional rather than beautiful.

Peek Pro invested in dashboard design and their analytics feel more modern. Real-time revenue tracking, booking pace comparisons, and visual reports are easier to access. However, the underlying data depth is shallower. Custom reports are limited, which frustrated several finance teams we've worked with.

<h3>Waiver Management</h3>

Peek Pro's built-in waiver system is excellent. Digital signatures, pre-arrival completion via email, minor consent handling, and integration with the booking flow all work smoothly. For high-liability activities, this integration alone can justify the platform choice.

Checkfront relies on integrations with dedicated waiver providers like Smartwaiver or WaiverForever. The connections work, but you're managing (and paying for) another system. The experience is slightly less seamless for customers.

